      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(discord): log warnings instead of silently swallowing component interaction errors",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\n`extensions/discord/src/monitor/agent-components-reply.ts` and `extensions/discord/src/monitor/exec-approvals.ts` use empty `catch {}` blocks to silently swallow errors from Discord interaction replies. When these replies fail (expired interaction, network issue, permission error), there is zero diagnostic output — making debugging impossible.\n\n## Changes\n\n- `agent-components-reply.ts`: `catch {}` → `catch (err) { console.warn(\"discord component reply failed\", ...) }`\n- `exec-approvals.ts`: 4 sites with `catch {}` → `catch (err) { console.warn(\"discord exec approval ... failed\", ...) }`\n\nLabel: bugfix | merge-risk: 🟢 minimal | AI-assisted\n\n## Evidence\n\n### Manual verification\n\nEach changed `catch {}` block previously silently discarded all errors. After the fix:\n- `replySilently()` logs `\"discord component reply failed\"` with the error message\n- `ExecApprovalButton` logs specific messages for each failure mode (unauthorized reply, acknowledge, followUp)\n\nThe `console.warn` calls are placed inside the catch blocks of Discord interaction reply methods, which are known to throw when interactions expire or permissions are insufficient. The warning includes the error message via `err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err)`.\n\n### Impact\n\nZero behavioral change — errors are still caught and execution continues. The only difference is that a `console.warn` diagnostic is emitted, allowing operators to detect and diagnose Discord interaction failures that were previously invisible.",
        "branch": "fix/discord-silent-catch-logging",
